<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="25" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="2.[189,798,688,1037]" pageId="2" pageNumber="25">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,319,688,712]" pageId="2" pageNumber="25">Diagnosis:</emphasis>
The hemitergal process on tergum 10 of the male forms a medially directed finger-like hook, which easily separates this genus from other genera in the subfamily 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Okamoto" authorityYear="1912" box="[504,682,797,821]" class="Insecta" family="Chloroperlidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Plecoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="25" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Chloroperlinae">Chloroperlinae</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Surdick, R. F." pageId="2" pageNumber="25" pagination="1 - 146" refId="ref2337" refString="Surdick, R. F. 1985. Nearctic genera of Chloroperlinae (Plecoptera: Chloroperlidae). Illinois Biological Monographs, 54: 1 - 146." type="journal article" year="1985">Surdick 1985</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Alexander, K. D. &amp; K. W. Stewart" box="[257,594,832,857]" pageId="2" pageNumber="25" refId="ref2012" refString="Alexander, K. D. &amp; K. W. Stewart 1999. Revision of the genus Suwallia Ricker (Plecoptera: Chloroperlidae). Transactions of the American" type="book" year="1999">Alexander and Stewart 1999</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Baumann, R. W. &amp; J. J. Lee" pageId="2" pageNumber="25" pagination="80 - 87" refId="ref2078" refString="Baumann, R. W. &amp; J. J. Lee 2014. Neaviperla is a valid stonefly genus in North America (Plecoptera: Chloroperlidae). Illiesia, 10 (9): 80 - 87." type="journal article" year="2014">Baumann &amp; Lee 2014</bibRefCitation>
) (
<figureCitation box="[274,346,869,893]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="1.[189,241,1835,1859]" captionTargetBox="[272,1302,264,1678]" captionTargetId="figure-90@1.[251,1385,218,1717]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="Figs. 1-6. Suwallia teleckojensis (Šámal 1939), male. 1. Terminalia, dorsal view. 2. Terminalia, lateral view. 3. Terminalia, dorsal view, after KOH treatment, 4. Aedeagus, ventral view. 5. Aedeagus, lateral view. 6. Terminalia with uneverted aedeagus after KOH treatment, dorsolateral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4760548" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4760548/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="25">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
). The general color of the adult is yellow with a distinct head pattern, U-shaped markings on the meso- and metanota, and a narrow, but distinct abdominal stripe that extends beyond the middle of the terga (
<figureCitation box="[568,657,1012,1036]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="3.[189,241,1275,1299]" captionTargetBox="[251,1385,254,1193]" captionTargetId="figure-321@3.[251,1385,254,1193]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Figs. 7-8. Suwallia teleckojensis (Šámal 1939). 7. Male habitus, dorsal view. 8. Female habitus, dorsal view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4760550" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4760550/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="25">Fig. 7-8</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
